# Backend Engineering

## Dependency Rule (never reverse)

```
Route Handler / Server Action
  → Validator (Zod)
  → Policy (authorization)
  → Application Service (workflow)
  → Repository (Prisma access)
  → PostgreSQL
```

## Layer Responsibilities

| Layer | Owns | Never Owns |
|-------|------|------------|
| Route Handler | GET reads, cron entry | Business logic |
| Server Action | Parse input, delegate, map envelope | SQL, auth decisions |
| Service | One workflow, transaction boundary | SQL details, auth checks |
| Policy | `canView`, `canAllocate`, dept scope | Business validation |
| Repository | Persistence queries | Business decisions |

## Rules

- **One workflow = one service**: `AllocateAssetService`, not `AssetService`
- **Every module has one repository from day one** — small, focused, no generic base
- Repositories never call other repositories; services orchestrate
- Transaction boundaries open in services via `withTransaction()`
- Functions ~20–40 lines; services stay focused

## Anti-Patterns

- Business logic in Server Actions or Route Handlers
- Prisma calls directly in services (use repository)
- `BaseService`, `AbstractRepository`, `GenericRepository`
- God classes handling unrelated workflows

## Module Isolation

Modules depend on `shared/` only — never import from other feature modules.

Cross-module orchestration happens in services calling multiple repositories within one transaction.
